uage=EN>infestedmatrix</A> at: 10/7/01 4:26:40 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ufalcondelta.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FalconDelta</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(10/7/01 9:36:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=342.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://hipolymer.virtualave.net/images/Delta.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Team of fantasy/action writers</span><hr size=1> ( this is a long string, but i outline the basics of a story, sorry if there are typos, I didnt have much time to proof it)<br>
I kinda like the space city idea. It gives more leverage to touch on political issues of our current societies, such as city pollution, over crowding, etc etc. The broken down fantasy city is good, but hackneyed. I agree the space city idea isn't anything novel either, but it would allow the razor to have a sharper and more defined edge. Also your superhero is a bit cliche, not a bad start, but its not quite realistic enough. He's got skill, women, and super powers...its fantasy, but that alienates the reader way too much, no one could ever relate to that. That sort of character would work well if we were writing a sort of satiric-comic in which we present the main character as someone who thinks he is super-human, but as we find out in the story he encounters one mishap after another. If we have a comic in our midst this may be an angle you want to take, but most likely the protagonist will have to have a slightly more realistic back. <br>
 Here is the idea I had, <br>
We start out on the space polluted whatever city, per gothics suggestion, the opening scene is our main character sitting in some classy type bar, but he's in the back corner, amongst a more subdued lighting, not dark, but shadowed. This gives a sense of ambiguity. He's inbetween being in total darkness and being fully in the light. This can be at times used to mimic both his physical and mental state and can be incorporated as a motif. He is unsure of the life he wants to live, hence he is now traveling the middle road, but the road is an over-used way to show this, I much prefer the light-dark method, since it can have other implications which are applicable to our story. The main character is an assasin, but he hasn't killed anybody in a while, he's a bit out of practice as a first encounter shows, but quickly gets back into the groove. He's the descendent of some Earl on the planet so he has money, when he's out he dresses well ( i.e. clean pressed suit, tie, etc) and attracts women constently, but since he is an assasin he can never have any of them. Usually his encounters in this way are brief, lasting one or two nights only. ( we can use this to touch subtly, on the frivolity that exists between men and women in society now adays.) We find out that his rich business type brother has just been killed, and he is out to get the killers. This however is only a sub-plot leading to a much larger one. He is somewhat alienated from the rest of his more aristocratic family, hence his location in such a city. The business with his brother is that he got involved with a syndicate and the deal went south. When our main character gets finished takin out the people that killed his brother, he meets a woman who has heard about his family and is on intimate terms with the lads uncle. She's the main character's age, and by intimate i mean she knows his uncle well, they're not invloved sexually. Anywho, The main character is always wanting to get back to his family again. This woman offers him a 'connection to the past' essentially. We learn that our protagonist somehow left his family with his brother of 15 years senior, for some reason in the past. At this time the protagonist was too small to know the real reason. Now after meeting this woman he begins to find out more of the story about his family's past, but why he left and why he can't get back is still unclear. After his uncle reveals some troubling information about the past, (his family controlled by subvert assasination the politics of a planet for several centuries and it was fated that one day one of two moons would bring down the family) the one of two moons is our protagonist but he doesnt know this. As his uncle is about to reveal the nature of the protagonists exit from his family, he is killed. Leaving the girl hurt, she falls back on the protagonist for housing and protection. But he feels that it is difficult to provide this due to the nature of his work and this becomes a real burden for him (at this point he stops seeing other women, because he feels he has an obligation to the girl), Things happen, he kills a few more people, and finally ends up in the old imperial city, run by a group known as the Pendants, touching on a frendship made in the initial chapters to a syndicate member, our protagonist with his friends help goes after the Pendats, soon he descovers however that the Pendents and his family are one in the same. The climax is he has to decide whether or not to kill his own father and the woman he had cared for, turns out she was leading him on all along (i.e. set up by the Pendants, although she is low on the food chain) She confesses that she loves him and but feared for her life all along and had no choice but to continue to obey the Pendants, since they were always watchin over anyway. The protagonist admits this to be the truth and accepts her love, as she never caused him any real harm and was on the most intimate of terms with him. However, he can not deny the atrocities that his family has comitted and assasinates the leaders of the Pendants, (his mother died helping he and his brother escape) he learns a few more things, the ending scene is he and the woman looking off from a hill on his estate into the distance. The implication is that they will still be together, but will never marry.<br>
Let me know what you think of this...<br>
-Falcon <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ugothicchaos.showPublicProfile?language=EN>gothic chaos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(10/8/01 12:52:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=342.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Team of fantasy/action writers</span><hr size=1> Nice idea falcon. Love that metaphore you were talking about. Nice outline, but there would have to be a few little sub-plots two get things moving.<br>
<br>
It seems though with the ideas i posted befor confused people. What i was trying to do was give diffrent examples on how something could be set up. Like &quot;something could be like this....or this....or perhaps this?&quot; But it seems it didn't matter, you guys seem very adaptive. <br>
<br>
As for the main character, how about he appears very sauve but underneath there is some dark secret or some sort of medical condition? Like a weakness? Next up is to develop this character further..<br>
<br>
Now on to the female character you mentioned. Being female i hate those type of women who are weak and such, and i've talked to other girls about books containing such characters. They didn't like them at all. So perhaps to get a better response, mabey she should excel at something rather difficult. Perhaps she could be an excellet fighter, or a intelligent scientist? Lets think about that.<br>
<br>
One last thing, as for the set up for the world. I like that space idea. Perhaps due to over crowding ect. people had to move out farther. There could be diffrent colonies on planets, each with there own diffrent enviroment, as well as large ships used for housing, transportation, buisnesses,schools ect.  If we did that there would a lot of contrast.<br>
<br>
I know i said the paragraph would be the last one but i lied....only one more okay? As to get action into this, Falcon's idea of the Pendents could give quite a few fight scenes. Along with that, since things will be in space there could be super nova's, black holes ect. in which our hero must escape. Also...a little humor relief would be nice, such as in a sarcastic backround character. One musn't be seriouse for to long. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/umylak.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mylak</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(10/8/01 1:16:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=342.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://mylakovich.homestead.com/files/pics/ngpclance.gif height=66 width=75></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> a few supporting ideas</span><hr size=1> well, lets see, if the character is an assassin, but he's rich and sees a lot of women, what kinds of things does he own? does he have a spaceship, or hoverbike, does he relate to poor people or does he always sport around in style?<br>
and if he is an assassin, that means that during fight scenes he should be able to waste a lot of generic thugs. what weapons does he use, and how does that relate to his personality. What devise will you use to give background information to the character, and what supporting characters are there that bring out certain characteristics in him? What stylizations will you include to make some things have more visual effect, you mentioned the light and dark, what other ideas do you have?<br>
